H0.text: Lymph is the watery fluid that bathes tissues and organs, contains protective white blood cells, and does not contain erythrocytes.

H1.text: Stomach is the watery fluid that bathes tissues and organs and contains protective white blood cells but does not contain erythrocytes.

H2.text: Basil is the watery fluid that bathes tissues and organs and contains protective white blood cells but does not contain erythrocytes.

H3.text: Secretion is the watery fluid that bathes tissues and organs, contains protective white blood cells, but does not contain erythrocytes.

A4.text: The lymph when formed is a watery clear liquid with the same composition as the interstitial fluid.

A5.text: Lymph that leaves a lymph node is richer in lymphocytes than blood plasma is.
